</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ufurtivus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Furtivus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Boardfellow</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/16/02 10:28:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=804.topic&index=271>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Things you do after leaving a guild...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Now if only uilds (sic) got a million pieces of armor to distribute...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
But, that's my point.  Given enough time the various loot systems will equal out.  Perhaps it may take many years or more before it becomes equal, but the difference is that one system (equipping MT first) is much more effecient at stepping up to the next challenge from a time perspective than the other.  Hence, guilds choose it because they're not patient enough for the time it takes for the drops to even out.<br>
<br>
As an aside though, I am wondering how many people play EQ with a long term view (e.g. 10+ years).  If the history of MUDs is any indication, they don't really go away (even today I suspect you could find subscribers for the old NWN).  Eventually, EQ will stop further development and only run a skeleton maintenance crew.  And, they will eventually begin merging servers rather than splitting them.<br>
<br>
I'm curious how many subscribers it would take to maintain (and not grow) EQ.  Perhaps 10k?  Maybe they'll up the fees some to keep pace with inflation (though I suspect they will do some bundling deal with other VI online games).  Given that, I don't really see EQ shutting completely down and turning off the lights for many years (easily could go 10+ years).  Has EQ reached a point where it can perpetually sustain itself? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uwilrowe.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wilrowe</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Board Veteran</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/16/02 10:55:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=804.topic&index=272>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Things you do after leaving a guild...</span><hr size=1> I prefer to look at a mob's hate list as completely random, that way it makes the game slightly realistic. There have been several raids where casters die for no apparent reason when the MT was &quot;supposed&quot; to have controllable aggro. I'm not denying the importance of aggro management, than again I'm not going to praise it either.  <br>
<br>
Warrior hits Dragon for 100 points of damage<br>
Warrior hits Dragon for 25 points of damage<br>
Warrior hits Dragon for 74 points of damage<br>
etc<br>
etc <br>
etc<br>
Warrior is infused with the strength of Avatar<br>
etc <br>
etc                      &lt;--Two minutes of sole tanking passing by<br>
etc<br>
Enchanter begins to cast Tash<br>
Dragon glances nervously around<br>
Dragon tells everyone around him: &quot;You will not evade me Mr. Enchanter.<br>
Enchanter is summoned<br>
Enchanter is slain by Mr. Dragon.<br>
<br>
Like I said, it's very sketchy.<br>
