 <p>Lleauaric Fyrewynd<br>Sorcerer<br>Knight of Eternal Wrath<br>Ayonae Ro<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=3749">Gear</a>


</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/upalimaxsceleris.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Palimax Sceleris</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Local Resident</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/16/02 11:24:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=804.topic&index=274>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Things you do after leaving a guild...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Perhaps it may take many years or more before it becomes equal, but the difference is that one system (equipping MT first) is much more effecient at stepping up to the next challenge from a time perspective than the other. Hence, guilds choose it because they're not patient enough for the time it takes for the drops to even out.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I only disagree that our choice was based on impatience.  Equipping Allamar first makes us more efficient, and allows us to increase the drop rate -- which reduces the time necessary &quot;for the drops to even out.&quot;<br>
<br>
A little background.  I work for one of the larger IT/IS/IM consulting companies, and I consult to one of the larger healthcare organizations in the West.  I spend a lot of time making deployment tools.  I make packages to deploy software, machine images, and, amonst other things, archives of &quot;critical&quot; updates and fixes.  I'm attached to a virutal group called &quot;Enterprise Field Service Support&quot; which focuses mostly on standardizations and consolidations.<br>
<br>
One of the tools we use is a scripted installer for a particularly nasty patient record viewing application.  The development time of this tool took a few days of my time, and in return, reduced the average install time of the program suite from an hour of technician time to a half an hour of COMPUTER time with minimal interaction from the technician.<br>
<br>
I didn't do this because the technicians visiting machines in Field Service Support were lazy, or that they were too impatient.  I made the installer because it's more efficient to take the strategy that everyone benefits from in the long run.<br>
<br>
In Vision, we equipped Allamar first because (a) it's necssary, and (b) because it's more efficient.<br>
<br>
Don't confuse efficiency with a lack of patience.<br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
I don't want to suggest to anyone, for even a minute, that I'm trying to impose my guild's loot plans on ANYONE.  ...but I think it makes for interesting discussion. <p><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=4868>Palimax Sceleris</a>,
Guildleader: <a href=http://www.guildvision.org>Vision</a>, Grandmaster <a href=http://www.base-nine.org/available_tinkering_items.htm>Tinkerer</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/bayonaero.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=nydia>Nydia</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Board Veteran</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/16/02 11:32:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=804.topic&index=275>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Things you do after leaving a guild...</span><hr size=1> To Wilrowe:<br>
<br>
I have no experience on high end encounters, but I can say with certainty that some mobs, even in the &lt; 50 range, are more 'touchy' or 'spastic' about being provoked even after the MT has (theoretically) mucho agro than others of the same level.  And I have reason to believe that the *type* of spell provocation makes a difference too.  For example, ravishing drolvargs in DL are far 'touchier' to being slowed than say, the froglok forager in Trak, even though they are about the same level (frog is slightly higher level, usually).  And back when I was doing them, the Rathe HGs would routinely ignore tash of any agro was established at all, but come charging right at me once slow hit whether I had tashed beforehand or not, despite the fact that Tash(ania) is supposed to be a bigger 'agro hit'...  And, heh, *never* try to mezz the Rygorr chief when he is even or above to you, not only will he charge you when it doesn't stick, but so will all his friends... there wasn't even *time* to fire that futile stun off <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .<br>
<br>
I tend to believe that there *is* some rhyme and reason to mob agro, but that it is, to a significant degree, mob type specific.  Your level vs the mob's level also makes a big difference, once I hit my high 40s those drolvargs weren't *nearly* as eager to charge me anymore, even when I slapped the big taunt on...  It sure doesn't hurt though to take out as much 'insurance' as possible though in the form of buffed-to-the-teeth tankage doling out some hate and ill will before your half-naked casters start debuffing/nuking though...<br>
<br>
Sincerely,<br>
Nydia Ywalmoriel - 49th Enchanter of Tunare<br>
